{#- TL;DR (body) — canonical figures verbatim. #pbk-tldr-body = speakable. -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="pbk-tldr" style="padding-top:8px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">In one paragraph</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:16px;">What monthly bookkeeping costs.</h2>
    <div class="tldr-prose"><p id="pbk-tldr-body">Monthly bookkeeping at TechBrot is <strong>$400&ndash;$2,500+ per month</strong>, billed as a fixed monthly fee against a written scope &mdash; no hourly billing. There are three tiers: <strong>Essentials $400&ndash;$700/mo</strong> for low-volume single-entity businesses, <strong>Standard $700&ndash;$1,400/mo</strong> for established businesses with payroll and multiple accounts, and <strong>Complex $1,400&ndash;$2,500+/mo</strong> for higher volume, multiple entities, or class/department tracking. Four factors set your tier: monthly transaction volume, the number of bank and credit-card accounts reconciled, whether payroll is in scope, and the number of legal entities. It is always a range &mdash; your exact fixed fee is quoted in writing within 3 business days of a free discovery call. Tax filing isn&rsquo;t included (your CPA handles that), but a year-end CPA handoff is included free on every recurring engagement.</p></div>
  </div>
</section>

{#- FACTORS — four tier drivers → process-grid. -#}
<section class="sec reveal hub-rt--alt" id="pbk-factors" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">What sets your tier</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:22px;">Four factors move the number.</h2>
    <div class="process-grid">
      <div class="process-step"><div class="process-step__n">STEP 1</div><h3>Transaction volume</h3><p>per month</p></div>
      <div class="process-step"><div class="process-step__n">STEP 2</div><h3>Bank &amp; card accounts</h3><p>how many to reconcile</p></div>
      <div class="process-step"><div class="process-step__n">STEP 3</div><h3>Payroll</h3><p>in scope or not</p></div>
      <div class="process-step"><div class="process-step__n">STEP 4</div><h3>Number of entities</h3><p>one file per entity</p></div>
    </div>
    <p class="prose" style="font-size:13.5px;color:var(--color-ink-mute);margin-top:18px;">These four factors are what the free discovery call surfaces &mdash; nothing about your industry or revenue alone sets the price. The written scope reflects exactly where you land.</p>
  </div>
</section>

{#- THE THREE TIERS — canonical ranges from `tiers` data (untouched). -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="pbk-tiers">
  <div class="ct">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">The three tiers</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:10px;">Where monthly bookkeeping lands.</h2>
    <p class="lede" style="margin:0 0 28px;max-width:70ch;">The same fixed-fee model at every tier &mdash; what changes is volume, accounts, payroll, and entities. These are the canonical ranges; your exact fee is quoted in writing.</p>
    <div class="r-3">
      {%- for t in tiers %}
      <article class="ptier{% if loop.index == 2 %} ptier--featured{% endif %}">
        {%- if t.label %}<p class="ptier__flag">{{ t.label | safe }}</p>{%- endif %}
        <h3 class="ptier__name">{{ t.name | safe }}</h3>
        <p class="ptier__price">{{ t.range | safe }}</p>
        <p class="ptier__for">{{ t.body | safe }}</p>
        {%- if t.profile %}<p class="ptier__for"><strong>Typical profile:</strong> {{ t.profile | safe }}</p>{%- endif %}
      </article>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
    <p class="prose" style="font-size:13.5px;color:var(--color-ink-mute);margin-top:14px;">Representative profiles only &mdash; they illustrate the factors, not a guaranteed quote. Behind on the books before a recurring engagement can start? That&rsquo;s a one-time <a href="/pricing/cleanup/?intent=cleanup">cleanup or catch-up</a>, priced separately.</p>
  </div>
</section>

{#- INCLUDED — recurring monthly-close deliverables (baseline h3s). -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="pbk-included">
  <div class="ct">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">What&rsquo;s included</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:10px;">What every monthly tier includes.</h2>
    <p class="lede" style="margin:0 0 28px;max-width:70ch;">The recurring close work in every tier. Higher tiers do more of it, across more accounts and entities &mdash; the deliverables themselves don&rsquo;t change.</p>
    <div class="r-3">
      {%- for inc in included %}
      <div class="dc-card"><h3>{{ inc.name | safe }}</h3><p class="prose" style="font-size:14.5px;margin:6px 0 0;">{{ inc.body | safe }}</p></div>
      {%- endfor %}
    </div>
    <p class="prose" style="font-size:13.5px;color:var(--color-ink-mute);margin-top:14px;">What the bookkeeping work actually is &mdash; the monthly close in detail &mdash; lives on the <a href="/accounting/bookkeeping/monthly-bookkeeping/?intent=monthly">monthly bookkeeping service page</a>. This page is the price; that page is the work.</p>
  </div>
</section>

{#- WHY FIXED-FEE — prose. -#}
<section class="sec reveal hub-rt--alt" id="pbk-why" style="background:var(--color-paper-warm);border-top:1px solid var(--border-subtle);border-bottom:1px solid var(--border-subtle);">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="idx"><span class="idx__n">§</span><span class="idx__t">Why fixed-fee</span><span class="idx__rule"></span></div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:14px;">Why monthly bookkeeping is fixed-fee, not hourly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>Most bookkeepers bill hourly, and for recurring monthly work that is exactly backwards. The monthly close is the same shape every month &mdash; the same reconciliations, the same categorization, the same reports. Pricing predictable work by the hour just means your invoice swings with someone else&rsquo;s pace, and you can&rsquo;t budget the one line item that should be the most stable on your books.</p>
      <p>TechBrot prices monthly bookkeeping as a fixed monthly fee against a written scope. You know the number before the first close, and it doesn&rsquo;t move month to month. Ask questions, send documents, call when something comes up &mdash; there&rsquo;s no meter on your own bookkeeper. If your business genuinely changes &mdash; you add an entity, take on payroll, your volume jumps a tier &mdash; the fee is re-quoted and re-approved in writing before anything changes. <strong>You are never surprised by an invoice.</strong></p>
      <p>This works because the close is delivered by Certified ProAdvisors efficient enough to price it confidently. The fixed monthly fee is a statement of competence: we know how long a clean monthly close takes at your volume, so we can quote it. No long-term lock-in &mdash; recurring bookkeeping runs month to month against the written scope.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

